{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17653908","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17653908"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:49:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:49:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18593"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18593","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18593"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.67,0,0.04,0.04,0.25]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11325"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76054"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11325","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11325"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18593"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61555"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10296"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26239"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26246"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76054","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76054"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn action potential arrives at a presynaptic nerve terminal containing neurotransmitter-filled synaptic vesicles.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the next step in synaptic transmission?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Calcium enters through voltage-gated channels","Magnesium exits through ion channels","Chloride enters through ion channels","Potassium exits through voltage-gated channels","Sodium enters through ligand-gated channels"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen an action potential reaches the presynaptic terminal, \u003Cstrong\u003Ecalcium enters through voltage-gated channels\u003C/strong\u003E. This calcium influx is essential for triggering synaptic vesicle fusion with the presynaptic membrane and subsequent neurotransmitter release.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium enters through ligand-gated channels\u003C/strong\u003E - Sodium entry through ligand-gated channels occurs postsynaptically after neurotransmitter release, not presynaptically\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPotassium exits through voltage-gated channels\u003C/strong\u003E - While potassium channels are involved in action potential repolarisation, calcium entry is the crucial next step for neurotransmitter release\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChloride enters through ion channels\u003C/strong\u003E - Chloride channels are not directly involved in the presynaptic release mechanism\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnesium exits through ion channels\u003C/strong\u003E - Magnesium flux is not a significant component of synaptic transmission\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe calcium influx triggers SNARE proteins to facilitate vesicle fusion with the presynaptic membrane, allowing neurotransmitter release into the synaptic cleft.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Action potentials trigger calcium influx through voltage-gated calcium channels in presynaptic terminals.","Calcium influx causes synaptic vesicles to fuse with the presynaptic membrane and release neurotransmitters.","Neurotransmitter release requires both calcium and functional SNARE proteins for vesicle fusion."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Boron W. F., Boulpaep E. L. Medical Physiology. (3rd edition). US. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2017"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61555"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18593"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61555","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61555"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T23:07:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T23:08:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11325"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76054"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":n